om"},"da":{"1400 –17 September 1425":"1400–17. september 1425","1356–1429":"1356–1429","1419–1443":"1419–1443","1400–1425":"1400–1425","1425":"1425","1400":"1400","1356":"1356","1443":"1443","1400 ":"1400","1419":"1419","17 September 1425":"17. september 1425","1429":"1429","Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England":"Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom"," Cardiganshire, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales",", England":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1400 –17 September 1425":"1400–17 september 1425","1356–1429":"1356–1429","1419–1443":"1419–1443","1400–1425":"1400–1425","1425":"1425","1400":"1400","1356":"1356","1443":"1443","1400 ":"1400","1419":"1419","17 September 1425":"17 september 1425","1429":"1429","Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England":"Wrockwardine, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"," Cardiganshire, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales",", England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1400 –17 September 1425":"1400–17 September 1425","1356–1429":"1356–1429","1419–1443":"1419–1443","1400–1425":"1400–1425","1425":"1425","1400":"1400","1356":"1356","1443":"1443","1400 ":"1400","1419":"1419","17 September 1425":"17 September 1425","1429":"1429","Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England":"Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom"," Cardiganshire, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales",", England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Montague","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from either Montaigu-le-bois (Manche) or Montaigu (Manche, Aisne), named with Old French <i>mont</i> ‘hill’ + <i>agu</i> ‘pointed’ (from Latin <i>acutus</i>). Drogo de Montagud was a companion of William the Conqueror and founder of the <b>Montagu(e)</b> family, among whom the personal name <i>Drogo</i> was revived in the 19th century. Another family of the name <b>Monatgu</b> have held the titles of Duke of Montagu, Earl of Sandwich, Earl and Duke of Manchester, Earl of Halifax, and Earl of Beaulieu, and.","Irish: adopted as equivalent of Gaelic <b>Mac Taidhg</b> (see   McTigue  )."],"variants":[{"name":"McTigue","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Taidhg</b>, ‘son of <i>Tadhg</i>’, a personal name originally meaning ‘poet’ or ‘philosopher’. Compare   McCaig  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Montague was born in 1400, in Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. She married John Clement in 1400, in Cardiganshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 17 September 1425, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 25."},"et":{"1400 –17 September 1425":"1400–17. september 1425","1356–1429":"1356–1429","1419–1443":"1419–1443","1400–1425":"1400–1425","1425":"1425","1400":"1400","1356":"1356","1443":"1443","1400 ":"1400","1419":"1419","17 September 1425":"17. september 1425","1429":"1429","Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England":"Wrockwardine, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"," Cardiganshire, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales",", England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1400 –17 September 1425":"1400–17. syyskuuta 1425","1356–1429":"1356–1429","1419–1443":"1419–1443","1400–1425":"1400–1425","1425":"1425","1400":"1400","1356":"1356","1443":"1443","1400 ":"1400","1419":"1419","17 September 1425":"17. syyskuuta 1425","1429":"1429","Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England":"Wrockwardine, Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"," Cardiganshire, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales",", England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1400 –17 September 1425":"1400–17 septembre 1425","1356–1429":"1356–1429","1419–1443":"1419–1443","1400–1425":"1400–1425","1425":"1425","1400":"1400","1356":"1356","1443":"1443","1400 ":"1400",